">nced through the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Command Paper.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="color:#ce007c; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">EEF welcomes this inquiry which comes at an opportune time to allow industry to respond to the Government’s recent announcements around road funding and reform as announced in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Investing in Britain’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Future</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The views and requirements of i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ndustry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">often suffered from underrepresentation in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> debates about the strategic road network with the focus often placed on passenger</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and other non-freight traffic.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Manufacturers view the road</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> network as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">important</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, with four-fifths of respondents to a recent survey citing it as critical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to their business</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This importance is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">unsurprising;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the strategic road network is the glue that holds the rest of the transport network together linking local r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oads and businesses with ports, airports and the rail network. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition half of manufacturers say that the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> poor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> state of the UK’s roads significantly increases their operating costs. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The strategic and local road networks have been blighted by underinve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stment over decades </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a problem </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">compounded by a stop-start approach to investment.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Command Paper </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">represents a significant step in the right direction in providing long term certainty on road </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">investment. This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> combined with an expe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cted Road Investment Strategy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is a welcome new approach to delivering future road projects on the strategic road network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The Government should demonstrate commitment and progress by introducing the required legislation as swiftly as possible.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the mediu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m term it will be crucial to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">decide on a sustainable way forward in funding investment in the road network. Several options exist including the introduction of road user charging or a regulated asset base model. However </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">survey evidence shows that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">change would need to be done in a cost neutral way to get the support from manufacturers.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="color:#ce007c; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">How will the policies set out in the Government’s “Action for Roads” command paper improve the strategic road network for all road users, whilst also improving the en</span><span style="color:#ce007c; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">vironment?</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">EEF’s Transport for Growth</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> report identified that each kilometer of the UK motorway network carries more freight than any other major economy bar Japan and has two and a half times the passenger density of Germany’s network and three times that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of France.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Additionally, the number of on-time journeys on the UK motorway network is at a two year low a symptom of high levels of congestion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on the strategic road network </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and poorly maintained local roads. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The above factors are made worse by historic u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nderinvestment. Between 2005/06 and 2011/12 government capital expenditure on rail increased more than twice as fast as that on roads. By 2011/12 30% more was invested in the rail network than in roads.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The World </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Economic Forum Global Competitiveness Repor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> shows the effect of this underinvestment, with the UK slipping from 24</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to 28</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for the quality of our road infrastructure in the latest report.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Investment in the road network also suffers from stop-start uncertainty. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Poor transport infrastructure limi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ts business investment, but a stop-start approach further undermines the confidence amongst businesses that anything will get done. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Asked in 2012 how confident they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that transport infrastructure will improve over the next five years ba</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sed on stated g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment policy, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> negative balance of -2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">% was recorded in 2012 for the motorway network and -57% for local roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, by 2013 the comparable figures were -27% and -73% respectively.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">EEF’s Invest for Growth survey</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> showed that for manufacturers, qualit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y of infrastructure was the 4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> most important issue when deciding on which country to make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">capital expenditure investment.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">An often cited example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of stop-start investment decisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is that of the A14 route, a key freight corridor to the port of Felixstowe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Improvement schemes announced by the last Labour government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> originally cancelled by the Coalition Government in 2010, only to have funding reallocated in the recent Spending Round for 2015/16 with construction starting in 2016.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> repr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">esents a significant departure from this approach. The Highways Agency which manages and maintains the UK motorway network will be converted to a publicly-owned corporation and given five year funding certainty. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This departure from a stop-start </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">investment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strategy will provide clarity for industry to be able to plan and make investment decisions with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">clarity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on infrastructure intentions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">clarity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">includes not only where to invest (as we have seen above) but also the types of business activities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that can be introduced or strengthened.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">quality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">road network undermines investment plans for 59% of manufacturers looking to introduce new production strategies such as ‘just in time’ manufacturing, and serves as a barrier for 63% of manufacture</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rs in their attempts to recruit and retain employees</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. A stable and well outlined road investment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">package would enable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">some manufacturers to make long</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> term decisions in areas such as site acquisition or expansion.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Alongside this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> funding certainty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a Road In</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vestment Strategy will outline the major projects for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> commensurate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> five year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">period providing a forward look of planned road projects and when. Such a move will not only reinforce the investment certainty but allow suppliers to the road infrast</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ructure supply chain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to more appropriately plan recruitment and capital acquisition plans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">further reducing costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">achieving economies of scale to allow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> even more to be possibly delivered.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Infrastructure UK undertook an review of infrastructure costs an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d in relation to stop-start investment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> found</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 50.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“The lack of a visible and continuous pipeline results in poor incentivisation within industry to invest in people, develop innovative processes or purchase plant and equipment”</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></li></ol><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This cost review also found that in one highways maintenance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ject, efficiency savings of up to 10% were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">achieved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">due to the ability to plan and procure raw materials due to the certainty provided by a long term programme. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Finally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as part of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Action </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">for Roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> proposals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, a motorists champion will be established to hold a more independent Highways Agency to acco</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">unt on behalf of all road users including business and freight.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">problems identified with the strategic road network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> also come laden with their own negative environmental externalities. The most </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">acute</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> problem is con</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gestion, which as outlined </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">earlier </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">undermines business investment decisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the opportunity to introduce new production</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and operation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> methods. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">From an e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nvironmental point of view congestion also leads to an increase in carbon emissions. Studies have shown</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that vehicles travelling at 60km/h emit 40% less </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">than one travelling in stop-start conditions at 20km/h. Investment to reduce bottlenecks and smoot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h traffic flows will therefore not only improve business conditions but help to reduce the environmental impact of road travel.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="color:#ce007c; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">How does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes?</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> doesn’t directly link </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to other areas of Government transport investment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">planning or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">policy. Aviation policy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">requirements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are being </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">investigated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> separately as part of the Davies Commission, rail policy already exists in semi-isolation through its own five year ‘Control Periods’.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Linking transport modes through an integrated plan is important, not just for the creation of more seamless passenger journeys but businesses as well. As part of EEF’s Transport for Growth survey we asked manufacturers “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">From the perspective of issues your</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> company faces in growing your business, which UK transport network should be the highest priority for increased investment?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">” The results were clear, over 60% cited the road network as their highest priority, however the second highest priority </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">was integra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion of transport modes (13.3%) followed by aviation (12.3%), ports (6.9%) and rail (5.4%).</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This need for an integrated approach is one of the reasons EEF thinks an infrastructure commission is crucial in helping to look objectively at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">infrastructure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">investment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> requirements. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Such a commission would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">internalise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the benefits of independent analysis on complex, long-term infrastructure issues.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">EEF believes that such a commission would provide more timely, apolitical and expert input on long term infrastru</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cture issues and strategy. It would need to be able to set its own agenda, through the right of initiative thus ensuring that politically sensitive but crucial issues don’t get sidelined.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Crucially, this would mean identifying future infrastructure needs b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">efore they become a problem. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Additionally a commission would need to have the scope to suggest timescales for action, based on the required national need.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Finally, while such a body would need to be independent to maintain some legitimacy, it would also ne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed to be accountable. Such a body should report to Parliament – not Government to ensure such independence is maintained. An infrastructure commission </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would not be about taking politics out of infrastructure decision making, but about injecting robust and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">independent evidence into the debate around priorities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">An additional</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> benefit the new approach outlined in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> may </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bring</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is the opportunity to move from a reactive approach to planning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> road projects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> toward a more proactive approach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the long</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> term. With a more proactive approach comes the opportunity to more strategically link project development across different transport modes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The first Road Investment Strategy period and the level of funding devolved, provides guaranteed funding for all cu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rrently unfunded Highways Agency schemes. The Highways Agency should therefore have as an ambition for the second Road Investment Strategy for new projects to come attached with a modal appraisal of the expected traffic flows.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This could be achieved throug</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h working with the stakeholders such as Network Rail, to assess </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">traffic flows and the cross-benefits that can be achieved through different forms of transport, to help strengthen the business case for future projects.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The first Road Investment Strategy per</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iod should be seen as an exercise in much needed catching up on road investment.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Despite the lack of a direct link with planning in other transport areas, roads are the glue that brings together other transport modes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> outlined in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reight j</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ourneys to and from airport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, port</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and rail-freight interchanges all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">utilise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the road network. This makes investment and planning in the strategic road network that much more important, any action for roads should be seen as action for the entire transport network.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="color:#ce007c; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">What mechanisms are there for Government to increase investment in</span><span style="color:#ce007c; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> strategic roads and attract new investors? Are there good examples from other countries t</span><span style="color:#ce007c; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">hat could be applied in the UK?</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The July 2011 Fiscal sustainability report</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> highlighted the declining revenue take from transport taxes and charges</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the future</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Thi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s decline </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> primarily driven by vehicle efficiencies and an expected uptake in alternative fuelled vehicles. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">drivers will contribute to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a decline</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> revenue from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fuel duty and vehicle excise duty (presently the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> two</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> largest component of taxes pa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">id specifically by road users</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, leading to:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 50.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a share of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">GDP a fall in fuel duty receipts from 1.8% in 2010/11 to around 1% in 2030/31</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 50.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a share of GDP a fall in vehicle excise duty receipts from 0.4% in 2010/11 to 0.1% in 2030/31</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Report goes furthe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 50.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“Our analysis suggests that governments are likely to need to find replacement streams of revenue in the future[…] the response could be structured in such a way as to make the overall tax system more efficient.”</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While not the only factor behind a need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to change the way we fund investment in the road network, the changes in tax receipts are enough to begin a debate on how w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e increase investment levels or attract new investors to fund road infrastructure investment, particularly in light of the medium ter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m fiscal environment.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> However it is crucial to make clear that road charges and taxes are not hypothecated, nor should they be – the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">economic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">benefits derived from a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">functioning and effective road network accrue to all not just road users.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In looking at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the range of options</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> several </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">possibilities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> exist</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 50.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Seeking efficiencies in delivery</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: This is one route already being pursued in the maintenance of local authority highways through the Department for Transport Highways Maintenance Efficiency Programme (HMEP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">). However this would not be enough</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to meet the expected shortfall over the next two decades</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 50.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lowering technical standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: This includes declassifying roads to reduce or eliminate the required maintenance levels. While a route often pursued by rural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">councils, especially in light of recent harsh winter weather, such a measure would be unacceptable for the heavily used and business critical strategic road network.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 49.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Road user charge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: An option used in many other countries, where a charge is applied to cov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er the cost of maintaining the asset being used. The technology </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">exists for a national </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, particularly in light of the planned rollout of a national </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">non-domestic HGV road user charge. The HGV road user charge backs the principle of linking asset use to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> asset maintenance and reimburses domestic HGVs caught by the scheme, through the tax system. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 50.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As part of our Transport for Growth </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> we asked </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">manufacturers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to pick the various options under which they would support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a form of road user charging</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. More w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould consider supporting it if significant improvements in the existing road network could be delivered (44%) than those who wanted it just for new roads (29%).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This support was contingent on a fair deal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">being developed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with any charge being offset by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">redu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ctions in other taxes.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 50.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Tolling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: Similar to a road user charge, tolling is where users of an asset pay for the ability to do so. The Dartford Crossing and M6 Expressway are two examples with the A14 improvement scheme also consulting on the possibility of p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aying for its development costs through a future toll. While a useful stop gap measure it isn’t a whole network solution and toll payers may object to the principle of local users paying for improvements across the wider network. Tolls are also typical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sed for new road projects, not for maintaining existing assets.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 47.11pt; padding-left:6.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">PFI schemes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: These schemes are already in existence as part of the Highways Agency Design, Build, Finance, Operate programme. These schemes are funded by the private sector with payment charge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d based on a ‘shadow toll’ scheme. Under this scheme road use is monitored and the Highways Agency pays the private sector company based on use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the road. While a useful way of getting private sector involvement in the delivery of road infrastructure, pa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">yment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is taken from general taxation, the pressures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">highlighted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by the Office for Budget Responsibility would therefore not be wholly addressed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 50.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Regulated Asset Base model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: This model has been advocated by some as a way to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">drive up investment in the road n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">etwork from the private sector. It is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">modelled on the water industry and would involve </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a price-setting regulator </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overseeing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> investment fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">om private operators for a stable and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">capped return on investment paid for through user charges. While it has some meri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t, it is likely to prove difficult to remove political interference in the setting of price caps, as we have seen in the rail sector. Such interference would undermine </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the long</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">term</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> approach likely to be fostered through the Action for Roads reforms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, while</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> also creating a fragmented network of companies maintaining the asset base.</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The issue of future funding options is something which needs to be addressed now. The Transport Select Committee, as a cross party Parliamentary body, is well placed to look at th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e issue of future road funding in the round. Such a review would need to look at what taxes and charges are already paid for by motorists and how this could change in the future.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Building on the previous Transport Select Committee report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on road taxes and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">charges</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it would need to look at issues such as different charges for different uses (e.g. on and off peak) and the potential to leverage further investment off the back of any introduced charge.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Finally to ensure clarity amongst the public, it will be im</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">portant to identify the most pres</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sing need and stick to this as the communicated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rationale i.e. is the aim to charge for emissions, manage congestion or simply raise revenue in a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more sustainable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> way.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#ce007c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Transport for Growth, EEF, </span><a href="http://www.eef.org.uk/publications/reports/Transport-for-growth-Investing-in-our-infrastructure.htm"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:none">http://www.eef.org.uk/publications/reports/Transport-for-growth-Investing-in-our-infrastructure.htm</span></a></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> The Global Competitiveness Report 2012</span><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">-2013, World Economic Forum</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Connect More: CBI/KPMG i</span><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">nfrastructure survey 2013, CBI</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Invest for Growth, EEF, </span><a href="http://www.eef.org.uk/publications/reports/Invest-for-Growth.htm"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:none">http://www.eef.org.uk/publications/reports/Invest-for-Growth.htm</span></a></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Transport for Growth</span><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, EEF</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Infrastructure Cost Review: Main Report, Infrastructure UK, December 2010</span></p><p style="font-s